What is the role of screening?
he  criteria for a screening procedure to be justified includes: 1) he disease should be diagnosable at an early stage. 2) ood methods to evaluate disease progress should exist. 3)  treatment that improves prognosis must exist. , , long , arfanβ€™s syndrome, aortic stenosis and coarctation of the aorta all easily fulfil these criteria. aken together however (see able 3), the incidence is around 1.82/1000, and in the view of most authors is not high enough to merit a systematic population screening program. owever, directed screening to high risk groups is eminently justified, in particular to first degree relatives of patients with inherited heart disorders, but also to individuals engaging in high risk activity such as organized sport.
everal working parties from the merican eart ssociation ouncil and from the uropean ociety of ardiologists have concluded that preparticipation screening is advisable for individuals engaged in athletic activity,21,22 but there is a transatlantic disagreement about the form of screening with the merican document recommending screening with history and physical examination only, whereas the uropean document suggests also including a routine -screening, as does the nternational lympic ommittee.23 here has been a heated debate about these suggestions, and some poorly documented figures about number of β€�false positivesβ€� of -screening have been bandied about as an argument for not including -screening. or example, based on criteria of -normality in sedentary individuals, a college athlete study is often quoted as showing that  has a β€�false positive rate of 20%β€�, whereas in fact only 11% had -findings as the only positive screening finding.24 he figure of 20% has also been vigorously rebutted by a large study on 32,652 unselected subjects undergoing preparticipation cardiovascular screening in taly.25 his study showed a normal  in 88.2%, and some abnormality in 11.8%. owever some of these abnormalities were mild and known to be associated with regular physical training (mild prolongation of -interval, incomplete right bundle branch block, and early repolarization pattern) accounted for 7 out of the 11.8%). he -abnormalities considered more suggestive of cardiac disease were deep -wave inversion in at least 2 precordial and/or standard leads (2.3%), increased -voltages suggesting -hypertrophy (0.8%), complete right bundle branch block (1.0%), left anterior fascicular block (0.5%), left bundle branch block (0.1%), pre-excitation (0.1%), and surprisingly few prolonged c (0.03%). hus only 4.8% had -abnormalities that by themselves indicated further investigations according to the authors.25 nfortunately this study was limited by not having access to the diagnostic tests performed and final diagnosis reached in the -positive individuals. herefore assessing from this study how many of the 4.8% were false positives, or if there were any important false negatives among the individuals with minor or no -abnormalities, is not possible. ertainly, in other contexts it has been reported that patients with  failed to come out positive in the standard talian screening protocol.4 hat the talian screening approach has tangible effects in reducing mortality in athletes has, however, been clearly shown.4 ortunately aggish et al have carried out the first prospective screening study that compared the outcome of screening with history and examination with and without , to the findings on echocardiography that was performed on all subjects (and further diagnostic work-up as indicated).26 mong 510 college athletes, age 18 or above, there were 11 individuals identified considered at potential risk from sports participation. istory and examination alone detected 5 (sensitivity 45.5%; 95%  16.8%β€“76.2%) whereas the addition of  detected a further 5 (sensitivity 90.9%; 95%  79.1β€“86.0). he false positive rate for history and examination alone was 5.5%, compared with a false positive rate of 16.9% when  was added. fter further detailed work-up, 3/11 were disqualified from athletics, and only 1 out of those 3 had been detected with screening without .26 he authors used standard -criteria for sedentary individuals and commented that their false positive rate would have been lower if a novel  algorithm had been developed that would differentiate physiological remodeling from pathologic heart disease in athletes. imultaneously, a large cost-effectiveness study concluded that addition of  to preparticipation screening would save 2.06 additional life-years per 1000 athletes screened, with a cost-effectiveness of $42,900 per life-year saved, whereas screening with history and examination alone saved only 0.56 life-years per 1000 athletes screened, at a cost of $199,000 per life year saved.27 he authors concluded that screening based on history, examination, and  saved 2.6 life-years per 1000 athletes screened, and that the cost was reasonable, whereas screening with history and examination alone was poor value for money. hey also suggested that a higher threshold for -positivity, and that organized mass screening of young athletes, should bring down costs, whereas annual screening of all school students was unlikely to be cost-effective.27
ore specific criteria for -screening of athletes have indeed recently been suggested by orrado et al.28 t is a large document, with many useful  illustrations, but occasionally suffers from being written purely from an adult cardiologistβ€™s perspective, and includes recommendations about the subsequent cardiological work-up of individuals with suspected cardiac findings.  have therefore tried to summarize their recommendations in able 4, also taking account of the findings in young athletes reported by harma et al.29 here have been reports that -wave inversion across several precordial leads is more common in fro-aribbean than in aucasian athletes,30 which has led some authors to suggest different and laxer criteria for fro-aribbean athletes. t the same time the large merican review of deaths among athletes showed a considerable excess mortality among fro-aribbean athletes caused by ,3 a diagnosis where precordial -wave changes may precede severe hypertrophy.31 ertainly, in a large follow-up of talian athletes who had abnormal -wave changes on preparticipation screening, but who were cleared for participation as no definite abnormalities were found on standard echocardiography, 1/84 died suddenly during sports activity with a postmortem diagnosis of arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy; of the 81 subjects with follow-up 5/81 (6%) later developed overt cardiomyopathy, and 6/81 other cardiovascular disease, so that in total 11/81 (13.6%) had undetected cardiovascular disease.32 urthermore, the ability to detect as many cases of  as possible rests with doing further assessment of all patients with -wave inversion in leads 3β€“4. onsequently my recommendation is that all individuals with abnormal -wave inversion for age should be referred for detailed echocardiography including tissue oppler assessment of diastolic relaxation and longitudinal systolic function. ome authors have suggested that the normalization of -wave inversion on exercise means that it is innocent, but that is not necessarily true, as it is seen, for example, in patients with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy due to absence of glycogen synthesase.33 n -scoring system for assessing the risk of sudden death in patients with  has been proposed, which has a sensitivity of 85% for  related sudden death, and a specificity of 100%, ie, 0% false positives among a group of 34 athletes. sing this score will certainly have high sensitivity in detecting patients with  at risk for sudden death.34 his score approach might be developed, by including more features suggestive of , to be used for general athlete screening, but will first need to be tested in a larger group of athletes before being generally adopted for screening. ased on studies from tertiary referral centers researchers have claimed that in the vast majority of patients with , 75% to 95%, have abnormal s, making -screening effective.2 his is however not correct for young  patients <18 years of age identified through cascade screening, where only around 56% have -abnormalities, if 12-lead  amplitude sum >24 m. V is counted as a diagnostic abnormality.35 However, the latest proposal from Corrado et al is that ECG-amplitude voltages should be ignored when screening athletes.28 The ECG shown in Figure 1 illustrates that this suggestion poses a dilemma. This was a 12-year-old boy who fainted during exercise (ie, high risk for sudden death), and where investigations established that he had obstructive hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. Yet the only abnormality on his ECG was that of voltages: Sokolowβ€“Lyon index of 5.8 mV, limb lead QRS-amplitude sum of 11.7 mV (fulfilling pediatric high-risk criteria in HCM,36 and a 12-lead amplitude voltage sum of 31.5 mV). Konno et al showed that 12-lead QRS amplitude voltage sum of >24 mV, and a Romhiltβ€“Estes score of β‰¥4 were the most sensitive ECG measures to identify genetically verified HCM, with a false positive rate of 5%.37 The comment of Baggish in an author reply β€�t