<sections.7>
How should screening be performed?
here is general consensus that a history should be taken, which includes questions on a family history of unexpected sudden death below 50 years of age, knowledge of a family member with symptomatic heart disease below 50 years of age, and any knowledge of heart muscle disorders, arrhythmia problems or arfanβ€™s or long -syndrome. urther, any existence of symptoms such as heavy chest pain, or abnormal breathlessness on exertion, episodes of palpitations, previous episodes of faints or sudden near fainting episodes should be ascertained. oth  and , as well as coronary artery malformations, may have exercise-related symptoms that for years are misinterpreted as exercise-induced asthma. ny previous findings of heart murmur or elevated blood pressure should be recorded. his could initially be established by a questionnaire, which also allows young athletes to consult their parents for the family history.hysical examination should include listening for cardiac murmurs precordially and over the back, measuring the blood pressure in the right arm, palpating the femoral pulses, and to visually assess possible stigmata of arfanβ€™s syndrome, including measuring span (or sitting height) on all individuals with a height >2  for age. ppearances suggestive of oonanβ€™s syndrome are also relevant, in view of the high correlation with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. resting  should be taken. f resting  shows, eg, very marked sinus bradycardia or ventricular ectopics, it could be combined with a simple instantaneous limited exercise with a repeat  after a simple step-test, or repeated sit-ups, to assess how heart rate increases, and how ventricular ectopics repond to a faster sinus rhythm (should disappear at heart rates >110). he best current experience suggests that the  should be judged according the criteria in able 4, and that those positive should be referred to detailed echocardiography before being cleared for participation in sports, or to 24-hour  and exercise test in case o