How do you best differentiate physiological hypertrophy in an athlete, the so-called β€�athleteβ€™s heartβ€�, from hypertrophic cardiomyopathy?
egular physical training by itself is associated with cardiac remodelling and cardiac hypertrophy, which in endurance athletes consists of a proportional increase in wall thickness and cavity size, so that the wall:cavity ratio remains normal.39β€“42 dditional isometric training such as weight lifting can cause more concentric hypertrophy. n one study on elite athletes (lympic candidates) only 16 out of 947 athletes had a wall thickness of 13 mm or above, and 15/16 were rowers or canoeists.43 he wall-to-cavity ratios have a great advantage for screening in having the same normal values for males and females,42 and normal values from birth to young adults have been published.42 he normal values increase marginally during the pubertal growth, and the normal values for those ages relevant for preparticipation screening (range 6β€“35) are given in able 5. ormal values for junior athletes were not significantly higher, being 0.19 (± of 0.03) for left ventricular wall-to-cavity ratios, and 0.19 (±0.02) for septum-to-cavity ratio.42 lder endurance athletes also had a septum-to-cavity ratio of 0.19 (±0.02). lite rowers instead had an average septum-cavity ratio of 0.23 (±0.03), with 2/17 having a septum-to-cavity ratio >0.26, ie, they would be false-positives on screening using 99% prediction limits in normals for septum-to-cavity ratio as a cut-off.41 owever, typical for the athleteβ€™s heart is that the circumferential contractility is normal, or even low-normal, whereas circumferential contractiliy in  patients, particularly young ones, is often increased. his could be used to differentiate between physiological hypertrophy (athleteβ€™s heart) and , because a cut-off of systolic wall-to-cavity ratio of >0.63 has a 94% detection rate for , and 0% false positive rate for athletes.41 ongitudinal function is often supernormal in athletes,44 whereas it is often reduced in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy,45 and this can be measured simply with systolic  (atrioventricular)-plane ex